# Mood Journaling API (Backend)
📘 A lightweight, expressive journaling API built with FastAPI, SQLModel, and SQLite. This backend powers a mood‑tracking application where users can record daily entries, retrieve past reflections, and build a long‑term emotional history.
This project is part of a full‑stack portfolio build, designed to demonstrate backend fundamentals, clean architecture, and professional development practices.

🌿 Overview
What the API Does
- Accepts new mood journal entries with a date, mood rating, and optional note
- Stores entries in a SQLite database using SQLModel
- Retrieves individual entries or all entries
- Provides a health check endpoint for uptime monitoring
- Includes validation and error handling for clean, predictable responses
Tech Stack
- FastAPI — high‑performance Python web framework
- SQLModel — ORM built on SQLAlchemy + Pydantic
- SQLite — simple, file‑based relational database
- Uvicorn — ASGI server for running FastAPI
Purpose
This backend is the foundation of a full‑stack journaling application. It demonstrates:
- API design
- Data modeling
- Validation
- Error handling
- Environment setup
- Professional project structure
It is built as a portfolio project to showcase backend engineering skills.

⚙️ Setup Instructions
These steps assume you are inside the project’s backend/ directory.
1. Create and activate a virtual environment
Windows (PowerShell)
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate


You should see:
(venv)


If not, ensure VS Code is opened to the backend folder, not the project root.
2. Install dependencies
pip install fastapi sqlmodel uvicorn


(You may also install black and isort for formatting.)
3. Run the server
uvicorn app.main:app --reload


You should see:
Uvicorn running on http://127.0.0.1:8000


4. Access the interactive API docs
Open:
http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs


FastAPI automatically generates a full Swagger UI for testing endpoints.

🔌 Endpoints
POST /entry
Create a new journal entry.
Request Body
{
  "date": "2024-01-01",
  "mood": 4,
  "note": "Feeling good today"
}


Response
Returns the created entry with an auto‑generated id.

GET /entry/{id}
Retrieve a single entry by its ID.

GET /entries
Retrieve all entries in the database.

GET /health
Simple health check endpoint.
Response
{
  "status": "ok"
}



🛠️ Troubleshooting & Common Pitfalls
These are real issues encountered during development — and how to fix them quickly.

1. “SQLite Date type only accepts Python date objects” (500 error)
Cause:
Your POST endpoint is receiving a string instead of a Python date object.
Fix:
Use a separate request model:

class EntryCreate(SQLModel):
    date: date
    mood: int
    note: Optional[str] = None


Then convert it:
db_entry = Entry(**entry.dict())



2. FastAPI or SQLModel imports show yellow squiggles in VS Code
Cause:
VS Code is using the wrong Python interpreter.
Fix:
Open VS Code to the backend folder, then:
Ctrl + Shift + P → Python: Select Interpreter


Choose:
backend/venv/Scripts/python.exe


If needed, create:
backend/.vscode/settings.json


With:
{
  "python.defaultInterpreterPath": "C:\\path\\to\\backend\\venv\\Scripts\\python.exe",
  "python.terminal.activateEnvironment": true
}



3. Terminal doesn’t auto‑activate the venv
Cause:
VS Code workspace root is wrong.
Fix:
Open VS Code to:
mood_journaling_app/backend


Then open a new terminal.

4. “fatal: not a git repository”
Cause:
Git was not initialized at the project root.
Fix:
cd mood_journaling_app
git init



5. “Please tell me who you are” (Git identity error)
Fix:
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your_email@example.com"
